<TITLE> Burundi secondary school teachers end strike </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BUJUMBURA, Oct 24 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Thousands of secondary school teachers in Burundi suspended a 2-1/2-week-old strike on Wednesday after the government agreed to hand over unpaid salaries. "We decided to return to work because the government promised to pay part of our overdue salaries by November and the rest in the first three months of 2008," Philbert Ngezahayo, head of the secondary school teachers' union, told reporters. On Tuesday, nearly 30,000 primary school teachers in Burundi launched a separate strike over pay and conditions. Teachers account for nearly three-quarters of all Burundi's civil servants, and currently earn between $25 and $35 a month. The government has pledged to boost public employees' salaries by up to 34 percent by next year, but the International Monetary Fund has urged the authorities to raise revenues fir
